Sure, I can provide more information on handling different file types and MIME types in the Rust web server. In the initial example, the Rust web server serves static files from the `public` directory. However, it assumes that all files have the same MIME type. To handle different file types and MIME types, you can modify the `Static` middleware to use a custom MIME type for each file extension. Here's an example of how to modify the `Static` middleware to handle different file types and MIME types:

```
use staticfile::{Static, MimeOverride};

let mut static_handler = Static::new(Path::new("public")).gzip(GzipWriter::new());

// Define custom MIME types for each file extension
let mime_override = MimeOverride::new()
    .add_extension_override("css", "text/css;charset=utf-8")
    .add_extension_override("js", "application/javascript;charset=utf-8")
    .add_extension_override("png", "image/png")
    .add_extension_override("jpg", "image/jpeg")
    .add_extension_override("gif", "image/gif")
    .add_extension_override("svg", "image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8");

static_handler.set_mime_override(mime_override);

mount.mount("/", static_handler);
```

This code defines custom MIME types for each file extension using the `MimeOverride` struct from Staticfile. You can add custom MIME types for any file extension you want to support. This allows clients to properly interpret the file type, which can improve rendering speed and avoid errors. You can also use third-party crates for handling more complex file types. For example, if you want to serve WebP images, you can use the `image` crate to convert JPEG and PNG images to WebP format. Here's an example of how to use the `image` crate with the Rust web server:

```
use staticfile::{Static, MimeOverride};
use image::jpeg::JPEGEncoder;
use image::png::PNGEncoder;
use image::webp::WebPEncoder;

let mut static_handler = Static::new(Path::new("public")).gzip(GzipWriter::new());

// Define custom MIME types for each file extension
let mime_override = MimeOverride::new()
    .add_extension_override("css", "text/css;charset=utf-8")
    .add_extension_override("js", "application/javascript;charset=utf-8")
    .add_extension_override("png", "image/png")
    .add_extension_override("jpg", "image/jpeg")
    .add_extension_override("gif", "image/gif")
    .add_extension_override("svg", "image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8")
    .add_extension_override("webp", "image/webp");

// Override the default encoder for JPEG and PNG images with the WebP encoder
static_handler.set_encoder_override(move |mime: &str, data: &[u8]| -> Result<Vec<u8>, ()> {
    match mime {
        "image/jpeg" => Ok(WebPEncoder::new().encode_from_jpeg(data, 75)),
        "image/png" => Ok(WebPEncoder::new().encode_from_png(data, 5)),
        _ => Ok(Vec::from(data)),
    }
});

static_handler.set_mime_override(mime_override);

mount.mount("/", static_handler);
```

This code uses the `image` crate to convert JPEG and PNG images to WebP format, which is a newer and more efficient image format with better compression than JPEG and PNG. The `set_encoder_override` method is used to override the default encoder for JPEG and PNG images with the `WebPEncoder`. This allows the Rust web server to serve WebP images to clients that support the format, while falling back to the original JPEG and PNG formats for clients that don't support WebP.

